\begin_layout Standard
In the gold-rush analogy, status consumption is the value of a signal that
 indicates a higher subjective likelihood of finding gold in the future,
 status consumption also provides the security of a shared belief among
 the risk-sharing consumers.
 A consumer who can let both herself and the other consumer believe that
 she is poised to find the next big mine with much higher wealth levels
 than their current fortunes would carry a higher status (regardless of
 whether she is the richer consumer or not).
 Similarly, a consumer may lose her status not simply due to direct wealth
 loss but through a disbelief in her future prospects as well.
 By ensuring that the consumers keep their risk-aversion levels close to
 each other, they attempt to ensure that their fortunes don't diverge too
