\begin_layout Standard
The above dynamics imply necessarily that the asset differences would be
 much higher than their starting point if a risk-taking consumer gets richer
 and the opportunities to gain mobility (return from the wealth process)
 dry up – thus leaving no chance for the poorer consumer to participate
 in the wealth game.
 To reduce final wealth differences and to leave the game in a state ripe
 enough until a natural process reinvigorates with more wealth, a taxation
 policy could provide an additional control to the wealth differences in
 the game.
 A taxation policy can be seen as simply a means to transfer a (linear)
 proportion of wealth differences from the richer consumer to the poor consumer.
 The tax rates remain constant throughout and their effect on the future
 income are known to the consumer.
 In the presence of risk-aversion, the above model for status consumption
 also helps us understand how taxation could influence consumer preferences
 among consumers with varying wealth levels and risk-aversion (in a rising
 and declining economy).
 The complexity of the model can be addressed with Monte Carlo simulations
 so that the stability condition is merely the point at which the consumers
 have run out of risk-taking opportunities (i.e.
 their disposable income have neared zero or costs balance the future expectatio
n of wealth changes).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
[Takeaways] 
\bar default
Instead of assuming wealth-differences we also focus on how the relevance
 of the knowledge of future across social sections could influence consumption
 more than the asset difference and income.
 This offers three advantages that are of value towards the normative theory
 for status consumption.
 First, we wish to arrive at a fair value of status consumption.
 Not all status consumption is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

waste
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 but is necessitated by asymmetries in future hopes not fully due to asset
 differences but probably socio-political changes that create different
 perceptions of the future.
 This allows us to under status consumption and its proposed futility in
 a wider contexts or in disparate economies (say in the developing and the
 developed world).
 Secondly, we get a more quantitative view of the effect of taxation on
 status consumption - by related it to the certainty of future wealth and
 behavioural approaches to risk.
 
\bar under
Taxation is straight money - but status consumption is risky consumption.
\bar default
Thirdly, this framework also allows an explicit way of endogenising social
 privileges in status by explaining the material impact merely subjective
 pecking orders.
